Local engagement as a countermeasure against populism
Paris – The parties that once dominated Western democracies have been shaken at their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered catastrophic election defeats.
And others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of the former president Ronald Reagan.
These developments are similar throughout the Western world.
The leaderships of the once-dominant parties oscillate between denial and despair, while populists reel in their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat andemean their supporters to their opponents as "pitiful," just as Hillary Clinton did shortly before losing to Trump in 2016; others are too terrified by the populist flood to launch a counter-offensive.
Neither denial nor self-satisfaction will dissolve the entrenched political situation.
The progressives must reposition themselves, and this begins with diagnosing the shortcomings of the traditional parties.
Part of the problem is that the traditional parties have failed to recognize the true issues of our time.
Still anchored on old ideological battlefields, they ignored declining social mobility, intensifying environmental crises, growing geographic inequality, tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that truly matter to voters.
They were the vanguard decades ago.
They stand alone in the forest, wondering where everyone has gone.
The social sciences might have an answer why the mainstream has strayed from its path.
The gap between their objective analysis of reality and government policy has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the increasing disparity in income and other indicators between some wealthy, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
Yet, before the French state president Emmanuel Macron's government did so, no national government chief had implemented tax cuts based on place of residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of France's GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
The traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to the voters instead of only through the filters of media and opinion institutes.
In 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the canvassers formed the basis of Macron's presidential election campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct, and Macron promised to address the issue if elected.
At the time, Macron's stance made him the target of his opponents' jokes; however, their laughter quickly faded with the rise of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They have long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and candidates rally supporters.
This was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to seize and hold power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, the established parties had several advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological advantage over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups capable of mobilizing people to the polls, organizing protests, and launching petitions.
But this model no longer works.
Citizens no longer want to be mere consumers of state politics.
Along with higher education levels, there emerged new demands for participation.
Voters want to be treated as political actors with their own rights, not as pawns in others' chess game.
Moreover, governments are no longer the sole providers of political measures.
This is one of the hard lessons we had to learn during the two years we worked alongside Macron at the Élysée Palace.
The most pressing political challenges today – climate change, religious extremism, digital transformations, and gender equality – do not allow for solutions solely by national governments.
These challenges require profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures on sub- and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to political participation, so traditional parties can no longer rely on the frontrunner bonus and solid support networks.
Who knows how to handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook doesn't need an ancient party apparatus.
Political movements must be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not just elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an operational "back office"; the front office should be staffed with people on the ground.
We refer to this as local citizen projects at En Marche!.
These can range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to community vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In each case, it is about offering tailored solutions to local problems and thereby strengthening communities.
One should consider such projects today as indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, the ability of a party to offer worthwhile paths for political and communal engagement will be crucial for its attractiveness.
And by demonstrating their reform policies daily "live," parties have already laid the groundwork for success at election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what one has to say, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win over the people.
Restoring the connection to the concerns of voters goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need a progressive policy on the ground.
